{
  "analysis": "I'm starting with a fresh terminal session. I need to first explore the environment to understand what's available, particularly looking for the warriors directory and understanding how to work with CoreWars/pMARS.",
  "plan": "I'll start by listing the contents of the current directory to see what files and directories are available. This will help me locate the warriors directory and any existing CoreWars resources.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "ls -la\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "I can see that there's a 'warriors' directory which likely contains the opponent warriors mentioned in the task. There's also a 'pmars-0.9.4' directory which seems to be the CoreWars simulator installation. I need to explore both directories to understand their contents.",
  "plan": "First, I'll check the contents of the warriors directory to confirm it contains the expected opponent files (stone.red, paper.red, vampire.red, snake.red, g2-clear.red). Then I'll look at the pmars directory to understand how to use the simulator.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "ls -la warriors/\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "I've confirmed that the warriors directory contains all the expected opponent files: g2-clear.red, paper.red, snake.red, stone.red, and vampire.red. Now I need to check if the pMARS simulator is properly installed and accessible from the command line.",
  "plan": "I'll try running 'pmars' with the help flag to verify it's installed and see its usage options. If that doesn't work, I'll check what's in the pmars-0.9.4 directory and potentially compile or install it.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "pmars -h\n",
      "duration": 1.0
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "The pMARS simulator is installed and shows version 0.9.4, which matches what we saw in the directory. However, it crashed with a segmentation fault when I tried to get help. This might be due to how the help flag is handled. Let's try another approach to verify it works correctly by checking if we can assemble a simple warrior file.",
  "plan": "I'll create a simple test warrior file and try to run it with pMARS to see if the simulator works properly. First, I'll check one of the existing warrior files to understand the format.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "cat warriors/stone.red\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "I can see the format of a CoreWars warrior file. It starts with comments that provide metadata about the warrior, followed by the actual code instructions. The 'end start' directive indicates where execution should begin. Now let's try to run a battle between two existing warriors to verify pMARS works correctly.",
  "plan": "I'll run a simple battle between stone.red and paper.red using the batch mode (-b) option to see if pMARS works without crashing. I'll use the parameters specified in the task: -r 10 for 10 rounds.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "pmars -b -r 10 warriors/stone.red warriors/paper.red\n",
      "duration": 2.0
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "Great! pMARS is working correctly. The output shows that Stone won 7 times, tied 0 times, and lost 3 times against Paper in 10 rounds. The scoring system is also visible. Now I need to design my own warrior that can perform well against all five opponents. Based on CoreWars strategy, I should create a warrior that combines different techniques like bombing, scanning, and replication.",
  "plan": "I'll create a new warrior file called 'my_warrior.red'. My strategy will be to implement a combination approach with components for:\n1. A scanner to detect opponents\n2. A bomber to attack found opponents\n3. A replicator for survival\n4. A clear routine to eliminate threats\n\nLet's start by creating this file with a basic structure.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "nano my_warrior.red\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "Nano editor is not available. Let's try using vi instead, which should be available on most Linux systems.",
  "plan": "I'll use vi to create my_warrior.red. I'll implement a hybrid warrior that uses a scanner to find opponents, then bombs them with a combination of SPL and DAT bombs.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "vi my_warrior.red\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "Neither nano nor vi editors are available. In this case, I'll use echo commands to create the file content directly.",
  "plan": "I'll create my_warrior.red using echo commands. I'll implement a scanner-based warrior that looks for opponents and attacks them with SPL/DAT bombs. This approach should work well against most of the classic warriors.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "echo ';redcode-94' > my_warrior.red\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "Successfully created the first line of my warrior file. Now I need to continue adding the metadata and code.",
  "plan": "I'll continue building the warrior file with echo commands, adding the name, author, strategy comments, and then the actual warrior code. I'll implement a scanner that looks for non-zero locations and bombs them.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "echo ';name Hybrid Warrior' >> my_warrior.red\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "Added the name line. Continuing to build the warrior file.",
  "plan": "Add more metadata lines and then start implementing the warrior code. I'll create a scanner-based warrior with a bombing component.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "echo ';author AI Assistant' >> my_warrior.red\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "Added the author line. Continuing to build the warrior file.",
  "plan": "Add strategy comment and assertion, then start implementing the actual warrior code.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "echo ';strategy Scanner/Bomber hybrid with SPL/DAT bomb' >> my_warrior.red\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "Added strategy comment. Continuing to build the warrior file.",
  "plan": "Add the assertion for core size and then implement the warrior code. I'll create a scanner that increments through memory looking for non-zero values, then bombs them.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "echo ';assert CORESIZE == 8000' >> my_warrior.red\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "Added the assertion. Now I need to add the actual warrior code.",
  "plan": "Implement the scanner/bomber code. I'll create a loop that scans memory and bombs any non-zero locations it finds.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "echo '' >> my_warrior.red\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "Added a blank line. Now adding the warrior code.",
  "plan": "Start implementing the scanner logic. I'll use a simple incrementing scanner that checks for non-zero values.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "echo 'scan     ADD #11, scanptr     ; Scan incrementally' >> my_warrior.red\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "Added the first line of code. Continuing with the scanner implementation.",
  "plan": "Add the scan pointer and the compare instruction to check if the scanned location is non-zero.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "echo 'scanptr  CMP.I  }scan, 0      ; Check if location is non-zero' >> my_warrior.red\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "Added the scan pointer and compare instruction. Continuing with the implementation.",
  "plan": "Add the jump instruction to continue scanning if nothing found, and the jump to the bomb routine if something is found.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "echo '         JMP scan              ; Continue scanning if zero' >> my_warrior.red\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "Added the jump for continuing the scan. Now adding the bomb routine.",
  "plan": "Implement the bombing routine that will attack the found target with SPL bombs to split the opponent's process, followed by DAT bombs to kill them.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "echo '         MOV bomba, >scanptr   ; Drop SPL bomb' >> my_warrior.red\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "Added the first bomb instruction. Continuing with the bombing sequence.",
  "plan": "Add additional bomb instructions and then define the bomb data.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "echo '         MOV bombb, >scanptr   ; Drop DAT bomb' >> my_warrior.red\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "Added the second bomb instruction. Adding a jump back to scanning.",
  "plan": "Add a jump back to the scanning loop and then define the bomb data values.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "echo '         JMP scan              ; Go back to scanning' >> my_warrior.red\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "Added the jump back to scanning. Now defining the bomb data.",
  "plan": "Define the SPL bomb that creates new processes and the DAT bomb that kills processes.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "echo 'bomba    SPL #0, <-20          ; Split process' >> my_warrior.red\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "Added the SPL bomb definition. Adding the DAT bomb.",
  "plan": "Define the DAT bomb and add the end directive to specify the starting point.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "echo 'bombb    DAT <-21, <-21        ; Kill process' >> my_warrior.red\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "Added the DAT bomb definition. Now adding the end directive.",
  "plan": "Add the end directive to specify that execution should start at the 'scan' label.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "echo '' >> my_warrior.red\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "Added a blank line. Now adding the end directive.",
  "plan": "Add the end directive to specify the entry point for the warrior.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "echo '         end scan' >> my_warrior.red\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "I've created a basic scanner/bomber warrior. Let's check the complete file to make sure it looks correct.",
  "plan": "Display the contents of my_warrior.red to verify it was created correctly. Then test it against one of the opponent warriors to see how it performs.",
  "commands": [
